\begin_layout Chapter
Real Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
The foundation on which the structure of higher analysis rests is the theory
 of real numbers.
 Any strict treatment of the foundations of the differential and integral
 calculus and of related subjects must inevitably start from there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rational numbers can be represented by points on a line.
 We shall see that there are gaps in this number line which will be filled
 by irrational numbers.
 The aggregate of rational and irrational numbers constitute the real number
 system.
 Rational numbers have a terminating or recurring decimal representation
 whereas irrational numbers have an infinite non-recurring and non-terminating
 decimal representation.
 A formal construction of the real number system will be taken up in subsequent
 sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rational numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Positive Integers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was to the numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,3,4,$
\end_inset

 etc.
 that we were first introduced through the process of 
\emph on
counting
\emph default
 certain objects.
 The totality of these numbers is known as the aggregate of 
\emph on
natural numbers
\emph default
, 
\emph on
whole numbers
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
positive integers
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

While the operations of addition and multiplications are possible in relation
 to the aggregate of positive integers, this is not the case in respect
 of the inverse operations of subtraction and division.
 Thus, for example, the symbols
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2-3,\,2\div3
\]

\end_inset

are meaningless in respect of the aggregate of positive integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fractional numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a later stage, another class of numbers like 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

 (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{4}$
\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are natural numbers, was added to the former class.
 This is known as the class of fractions and it obviously includes natural
 numbers as a sub-class: 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 being equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in this case.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The introduction of fractional numbers is motivated, from an abstract point
 of view, to render division  possible and, from concrete point of view,
 to render numbers serviceable for measurement also in addition to counting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rational numbers.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Rational-numbers."

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Still later, the class of numbers was enlarged by incorporating in it the
 class of negative fractions including negative integers and zero.
 The entire aggregate of these numbers is known as the 
\emph on
aggregate of rational numbers
\emph default
.
 Every rational number is expressible as 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are any two integers, positive or negative and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is not zero.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The introduction of negative numbers is motivated, from an abstract point
 of view to render subtraction always possible and, from concrete point
 of view, to facilitate a unified treatment of oppositely directed pairs
 of entities such as, gain and loss, rise and fall, etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental operations on rational numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important property of the aggregate of rational numbers is that the operation
s of addition, multiplication, subtraction and division can be performed
 upon any two such numbers, (with one 
\emph on
exception
\emph default
 which is considered below in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Meaningless-operation-of"

\end_inset

 ) and the number obtained as the result of these operations is again a
 rational number.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This property is expressed by saying that the aggregate of rational numbers
 is 
\emph on
closed
\emph default
 with respect to the four fundamental operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Meaningless-operation-of"

\end_inset

Meaningless operation of division by zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that the only exception to the above property is
 `division by zero' which is a meaningless operation.
 This may be seen as follows :--
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

To divide 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 amounts to determining a number 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
bc=a
\]

\end_inset

and the division will be intelligible only, if and only if, the determination
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
uniquely possible
\emph default
.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Now, there is no number which when multiplied by zero produces a number
 other than zero so that a 
\begin_inset Formula $a/0$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
no
\emph default
 number when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Also any number when multiplied by zero produces zero so that 
\begin_inset Formula $0/0$
\end_inset

 may be 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 number.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

On account of this 
\emph on
impossibility
\emph default
