\begin_layout Example

\emph on
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "recurring"

\end_inset

Show that every rational number is expressible as a terminating or a recurring
 decimal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
To decimalize 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

, we have first to divide 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and then each remainder, after multiplication with 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

, is to be divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to obtain the successive figures in the decimal expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

.
 The decimal expression will be terminating if, at some stage, the remainder
 vanishes.
 Otherwise, the process will be unending.
 In the latter case, the remainder will always be one of the finite set
 of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,\ldots,q-1$
\end_inset

 and so must repeat itself at some stage.
 From this stage onward, the quotients will also repeat themselves and the
 decimal expression will, therefore, be recurring.
\end_layout

