\begin_layout Standard
If possible, let its measure be a rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q$
\end_inset

 so that, by Pythagoras' theorem, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{p}{q}\right)^{2}=1^{2}+1^{2}=2,\mbox{ \emph{i.e.}, \ensuremath{p^{2}=2q^{2}.}}\label{eq:irr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 have no common factor, for, such factors, if any, can be canceled to begin
 with.
 
