\begin_layout Standard
Firstly we notice that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(2n\right)^{2}=4n^{2},\left(2n+1\right)^{2}=\left(4n^{2}+4n\right)+1
\]

\end_inset

so that the square of an even number is even and that of an odd number is
 odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:irr"

\end_inset

), we see, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an even number.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 itself must be even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an integer.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\qquad4n^{2}=2q^{2}\mbox{ or \ensuremath{q^{2}=2n^{2}.}}
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also even and so 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is even.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 have a common factor 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and this conclusion contradicts the hypothesis that they have no common
 factor.
 Thus the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $OP$
\end_inset

 is not a rational number.
