\begin_layout Chapter
 Rational Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
No science rests entirely within itself : each borrows the strength of its
 ultimate foundations from strata above or below it, such as experience,
 or theory of knowledge, or logic, or metaphysics, .
 .
 .
 Every science must accept something as simply given, and on that it may
 proceed to build.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We propose to regard at once as known (or given, or secured) a group
 of data whose deducibility from a smaller body of assumptions is familiar
 to everyone  namely, the 
\emph on
system of rational numbers
\emph default
, i.e.
 of numbers integral and fractional, positive and negative, including zero.
 Speaking broadly, it is a matter of common knowledge how this system may
 be constructed, if  as a smaller body of assumptions  only the ordered
 sequence of natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,3,...$
\end_inset

 , and their combinations by addition and multiplication, are regarded as
 given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Properties of Rational numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Order Properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rational numbers form an ordered aggregate; meaning that between any two,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, one and only one of the three relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a<b,\; a=b,\; a>b
\]

\end_inset

 necessarily holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:florder"

\end_inset

Fundamental Laws of Order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Invariably 
\begin_inset Formula $a=a.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a=b$
\end_inset

 always implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a=b,b=c$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a=c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a\leq b,b<c$
\end_inset

, --- or 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b,b\leq c,$
\end_inset

 --- implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a<c.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:fla"

\end_inset

Fundamental Laws of Arithmetic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any two rational numbers may be combined in four distinct ways, referred
 to respectively as the four processes (or basic operations) of Addition,
 Subtraction, Multiplication, and Division.
 These operations can always be carried out to one definite result, with
 the single exception of division by 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, which is undefined and should be regarded as an entirely impossible or
 meaningless process; the four processes also obey a number of simple laws,
 the so-called 
\emph on
Fundamental Laws of Arithmetic
\emph default
, and further rules deducible therefrom.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Addition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Every
\emph default
 pair of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 has invariably associated with it a third, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, called their sum and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a=a',b=b'$
\end_inset

 always imply 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b=a'+b'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Invariably, 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b=b+a$
\end_inset

 (Commutative Law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Invariably, 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)+c=a+(b+c)$
\end_inset

 (Associative Law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

 always implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a+c<b+c$
\end_inset

 (Law of Monotony).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Subtraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To every pair of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 there corresponds a third number 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a+c=b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To every pair of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 there corresponds a third number 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, called their product and denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $ab$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a=a',b=b'$
\end_inset

always implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=a'b'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In all cases 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

 (Commutative Law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In all cases 
\begin_inset Formula $(ab)c=a(bc)$
\end_inset

 (Associative Law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In all cases 
\begin_inset Formula $(a+b)c=ac+bc$
\end_inset

 (Distributive Law).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

 implies, provided 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is positive, 
\begin_inset Formula $ac>bc$
\end_inset

 (Law of Monotony).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Division.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To every pair of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 of which the first is not 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 there corresponds a third number 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ac=b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
All the known rules of arithmetic,  and hence ultimately all mathematical
 results,  are deduced from these few laws, with the help of the laws of
 pure logic alone.
 Among these laws, one is distinguished by its primarily mathematical character,
 namely the
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Law of Induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This may be reckoned among the fundamental laws of arithmetic and is normally
 stated as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a set of natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 includes the number 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and if, every time a certain natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and all those less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 can be taken to belong to the aggregate, the number 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

 may be inferred also to belong to it, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 includes all the natural numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This law of induction itself follows quite easily from the following theorem,
 which appears even more obvious and is therefore normally called the fundamenta
l law of the natural numbers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Law of Natural Numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In every set of natural numbers that is not empty there is always a number
 less than all the rest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For if, according to the hypotheses of the Induction Law, we consider the
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{N}$
\end_inset

 of natural numbers not belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 , this set must be empty, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

 must contain all the natural numbers.
 For otherwise, by the law of the natural numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{N}$
\end_inset

 would include a number less than all the rest.
 This least number would exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, for it was assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

; hence it could be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 would belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{M}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $(n+1)$
\end_inset

 would not, which contradicts the hypotheses in the law of induction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In applications it is usually an advantage to be able to make statements
 not merely about the natural numbers but about any whole numbers.
 The laws then take the following forms, obviously equivalent to those above:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Law of Induction
\emph default
.
 If a statement involves a natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (e.
 g.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geqq10$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $2n>n^{3}$
\end_inset

, or the like) and if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
a) this statement is correct for n = p, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
b) its correctness for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=p,p+1,\ldots,k$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is any natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $\geqq p$
\end_inset

) always implies its correctness for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=k+1$
\end_inset

, then the statement is correct for every natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Law of Integers
\emph default
.
 In every set of integers all 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq p$
\end_inset

 that is not empty, there is always a number less than all the rest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will lastly mention a theorem susceptible, in the domain of rational
 numbers, of immediate proof, although it becomes axiomatic in character
 very soon after this domain is left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Theorem of Eudoxus.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Theorem-of-Eudoxus."

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are any two positive rational numbers, then a natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 always exists such that 
\begin_inset Formula $nb>a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The four ways of combining two rational numbers give in every case as the
 result another rational number.
 In this sense the system of rational numbers forms a closed aggregate.
 This property of forming a closed system with respect to the four rules
 is obviously not possessed by the aggregate of all natural numbers, or
 of all positive and negative integers.
 These are, so to speak, too sparsely sown to meet all the demands which
 the four rules make upon them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
This closed aggregate of all rational numbers and the laws which hold in
 it, are then all that we regard as given, known, secured.
\end_layout

